Model Selection: 
Computer Vision & Camera: YOLOv9.
NLP & Text Classification: Hugging Face.
Image Classification: Roboflow
Decision Engine: Gemini Analysis
Reasoning:
Consolidated Vision Pipeline: We prioritize YOLOv9 for our core image and video processing to establish a strong technical foundation. Recent academic frameworks (such as TAERM) have demonstrated that YOLOv9 has the potential to achieve up to 0.951 accuracy in accident severity classification. While our prototype will establish its own baseline metrics, selecting YOLOv9 gives us a scientifically validated architecture over older models like MobileNet-SSD, which have been shown to struggle with complex traffic scenes.
High-Speed NLP: DistilBERT provides lightweight, resource-efficient natural language processing to rapidly parse citizen text reports without bottlenecking system memory.
Latency-Aware Synthesis: While GPT-4 acts as a powerful reasoning engine to synthesize complex multimodal data from citizen reports, relying on it for the entire system would introduce unacceptable inference latency. By restricting GPT-4 strictly to Pipeline B (Citizen Reports), our core YOLOv9 pipeline remains optimized for real-time edge processing.
SECTION 4: DATA STRATEGY & ETHICS
(Based on Workshop 2: Technical Architecture & Data Ethics)
Data Sources: Where will you get your data? (Open-source datasets, web scraping, synthetic data, or custom collection).
Our strategy relies on a multi-stream approach to build a representative dataset for the ASEAN context. We will utilize open-source urban datasets, such as the traffic accident repositories available on Kaggle, to provide a foundational baseline for our vision models. This is supplemented by synthetic data generation for emergency text logs to train the NLP pipeline and custom-collected samples to ensure regional relevance.
Data Quality & Cleaning: How will you ensure the data is accurate and relevant?
We ensure data accuracy and relevance by preprocessing text reports using Hugging Face (DistilBERT) to normalize input and classify emergency-related keywords. User input is validated through Node.js and Express.js to filter incomplete or invalid reports. Uploaded images are checked for validity before being processed with MobileNet. Data is then categorized into medical, fire, and police emergency classes, and tested using synthetic emergency scenarios to ensure relevance and consistent system performance. 
Visual Standardization: We utilize the Roboflow platform to preprocess all image data, ensuring consistent frame resizing and pixel normalization. We apply data augmentation—including rotation and scaling—to increase the model's robustness against varying environmental conditions.
Categorization: Data is sorted into four validated severity classes: normal traffic, trivial, medium, and severe accidents.
Validation: User-submitted reports undergo backend filtering via Node.js to remove malformed or irrelevant inputs before they reach the inference core.
